spec:
  type: ClusterIP
  ports:
    - port: 8080
      targetPort: 8080
  selector:
    opentelemetry.io/name: opentelemetry-demo-emailservice

ClusterIP means:

Only other Pods inside the Kubernetes cluster can access this service.

Pod A
   │
   ▼
Email Service (ClusterIP)
   ▲
   │
Pod B

Your laptop cannot access it.

Changing it to NodePort

You simply change the type and optionally specify a nodePort.

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service

metadata:
  name: opentelemetry-demo-emailservice

spec:
  type: NodePort

  ports:
    - port: 8080
      targetPort: 8080
      nodePort: 30080

  selector:
    opentelemetry.io/name: opentelemetry-demo-emailservice

Notice only two things changed:

type: NodePort

and

nodePort: 30080
What does each port mean?

This confuses almost everyone initially.

Let's assume:

Node IP = 54.210.15.20

and

port: 8080
targetPort: 8080
nodePort: 30080

Now think of the request journey.

Browser

↓

http://54.210.15.20:30080

↓

NodePort Service

↓

Service Port (8080)

↓

Pod

↓

Container Port (8080)
Meaning of each field
targetPort

Where is the application actually listening?

Suppose inside your container:

Email Service

Listening on

8080

So

targetPort: 8080

means

Forward traffic to port 8080 inside the Pod.

port

This is the Service's internal port.

Other Pods inside the cluster use it.

Example:

Checkout Pod

↓

emailservice:8080

Notice they never use 30080.

Inside the cluster:

emailservice:8080

works.

nodePort

This opens a port on every Kubernetes worker node.

Example:

Node 1
54.210.15.20

Port 30080
Node 2
54.210.15.21

Port 30080
Node 3
54.210.15.22

Port 30080

All of them forward to the Email Service.

Visual Flow
                    Internet
                        │
                        ▼
          http://54.210.15.20:30080
                        │
                        ▼
                 Kubernetes Node
                        │
                 NodePort (30080)
                        │
                        ▼
              Service Port (8080)
                        │
                        ▼
                   Email Pod
                        │
                Container:8080
Can I choose any NodePort?

No.

The default range is

30000 - 32767

So these are valid:

30001

30080

31000

32767

This is invalid:

8080

because NodePorts must be in the configured NodePort range.

What if I don't specify nodePort?

You can write:

spec:
  type: NodePort

  ports:
    - port: 8080
      targetPort: 8080

Kubernetes automatically picks something like

31245

You can check it using:

kubectl get svc

Output:

NAME           TYPE       PORT(S)
emailservice   NodePort   8080:31245/TCP

Here,

8080:31245

means:

Service Port = 8080
NodePort = 31245
Why don't we use NodePort in production?

Imagine you have 20 microservices.

Frontend

Payment

Checkout

Product

Recommendation

Shipping

Currency

Each would need a different NodePort:

30001

30002

30003

30004

30005
...

Users would have to remember:

myapp.com:30001

myapp.com:30002

myapp.com:30003

That's not practical.

Instead, in production we usually use:

Internet
     │
     ▼
Load Balancer / Ingress
     │
     ▼
Services (ClusterIP)
     │
     ▼
Pods

NodePort is often used:

for learning,
for testing,
or as a building block underneath a cloud LoadBalancer.
For your OpenTelemetry demo

If you changed the frontend Service from ClusterIP to NodePort like this:

spec:
  type: NodePort
  ports:
    - port: 8080
      targetPort: 8080
      nodePort: 30080

and your worker node had the public IP:

13.234.56.78

you could access it in your browser using:

http://13.234.56.78:30080

The browser doesn't talk directly to the Pod. The request flows like this:

Browser
    │
    ▼
Node IP:30080
    │
    ▼
Kubernetes Service
    │
    ▼
Matching Pod
    │
    ▼
Container listening on 8080

This is the key idea behind Kubernetes Services: they provide a stable network endpoint, while the actual Pods behind them can be created, destroyed, or replaced without clients needing to know their IP addresses.
